In this quadrant, the inequality simplifies to \( |x - 1| + |y - 1| \le 1 \). This represents a diamond (rotated square) centered at \((1, 1)\) with vertices at \((2, 1)\), \((1, 2)\), \((0, 1)\), and \((1, 0)\). The area of this diamond is calculated to be 2. Since the problem is symmetric across both the x-axis and y-axis, we consider the absolute values of \( x \) and \( y \). By substituting \( u = |x| \) and \( v = |y| \), the inequality becomes \( |u - 1| + |v - 1| \le 1 \) where \( u \ge 0 \) and \( v \ge 0 \). This region in the \((u, v)\) plane is a diamond with area 2. Each point \((u, v)\) in this region corresponds to four points \((x, y)\) in the original coordinate plane (one in each quadrant). Therefore, the total area in the original plane is four times the area in the \((u, v)\) plane, resulting in \( 4 \times 2 = 8 \). Thus, the area of the region defined by \( ||x| - 1| + ||y| - 1| \le 1 \) is \(\boxed{8}\).
